context: The most important river in Thuringia is <a0_0><b4_0>the Saale<b4_0/><a0_0/> (a tributary of the Elbe) with its tributaries Unstrut, Ilm and Weiße Elster, draining the most parts of Thuringia and the Werra (the headwater of the Weser), draining the south-west and west of the Land. Furthermore, some small parts on the southern border are drained by tributaries of <a3_0><b6_0>the Main (a tributary of the Rhine)<b6_0/><a3_0/>. <a1_0>There are no large natural lakes in <b7_0>Thuringia<b7_0/><a1_0/>, but it does have some of Germany's biggest dams including <a2_0>the <b5_0>Bleiloch Dam and the Hohenwarte Dam<b5_0/><a2_0/> at Saale river same as the Leibis-Lichte Dam and the Goldisthal Pumped Storage Station within the Highland. Thuringia is Germany's only state without connection to navigable waterways.
